  <span class="italic">C</span> and 
  <span class="italic">K</span> as functions of time corresponding to the Keynes–Ramsey rule and the capital dynamics:
  <div id="Equ20" class="disp-formula">
   <span class="label">A4</span>
   <div class="alternatives">
    <span id="M115" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ \begin{aligned} \dot{C}^{A} (t) &amp; = \sigma \left[ {Y_{K} \left( {K(t),\pi } \right) - \rho } \right]C^{A} (t), \\ \dot{K}(t) &amp; = Y\left( {K(t),\pi } \right) - C^{A} (t),\quad K(T) = K_{T} . \\ \end{aligned} $$\end{document}</span>
    <div id="M116" display="block" class="math">
